segments.text: So really, that's caused no problem.
And I think you'll see a higher percentage of women coming into reserve program and the Air Force in general in the future than you have in the past.
Are there some parallels between women coming into the military and the reserves and women being allowed here at A&M back in the 1960s?
I don't really see any.
Well, it's parallels as far as attitudes, initial resistance, which has changed.
Oh, OK.
I would presume so.
I would presume so.
But here, once again, after you get used to the idea and you see that it's going to work, then you accept it.
So there could be some parallels there, but I never thought of it in that context.
OK. Let's talk.
I'd like to talk.
I went over a number of your appointments.
and duties here.
And I'd like to talk about the development of the Air Force Reserve in the Bryan College Station area.
It looks like there was the 9807 ARS and then the 9412 ARS.
Could you explain that development?
I think at that particular time, that was more or less a change in designation of an activity more than an actual change in the mission or scope of the activity.
They were shuffling numbers like mad back in those times.
But as I recall, I don't recall there being any particular change.
I will say that in all of those time periods, the reserve program was nothing more than not much more
than a paper exercise and paperwork.
We had no equipment.
We had very little realistic training.
Our training consisted of taking correspondence courses in particular areas and trying to keep up what we call our general military training.
There are certain things that we have to go through annually, such as

The Uniform Code of Military Justice, we have to be familiar with that, not only so that we can watch other people, but so that we ourselves will know how to conduct ourselves under certain circumstances.
Things like communication security that we have to review every year to refresh on our minds that there are certain things you don't talk about on the telephone.
Those types of things, we were able to get those out of the way.
But as far as real gut training,
to qualify us to go into an active duty situation.
It was almost nonexistent in those days.
Now, let's clarify.
When were those days?
When was the first Air Force Reserve unit in this area?
I don't know, because it was here before I came in.
I went into the Air Force Reserves in this area in about 1960 or 61, as I recall.
After I got off of active duty in 1956, I was living in the Waco area.
and was assigned to a couple of units up in that area.
They were larger units, but they were primarily, once again, where we would meet and do the best we could with correspondence courses and lectures and talks.
But we had no field training.
We had no airplanes.
We had no equipment.
When I came from Waco here in probably 1959, 1960, in that time frame,
I immediately aligned with a reserve unit here locally, and I've even forgotten the number, but it would be the first unit that we had.
9807, yes, okay.
I found the same conditions to be true here that existed in Waco, and that is no equipment.

We, of course, all of us wore uniforms, and we spent a great deal of time on military courtesy and chain of command, span of control, all those kinds of things that are basic to any organization, military or otherwise.
We had the nucleus.
We had the people that wanted to do it.

And then after that, I really guess when the thing turned around for me, and when the reserves turned around, and you can find the date on it, was my first duty assignment at Ellington Air Force Base.
And I believe that was in the 9-25th?
That was 9-25th.
Tag at Ellington.
Any of these initials you need me to clarify for you, I can do that.
That's Tactical Airlift Group.
They had 119s.
That was the first unit I was ever in.
They had real airplanes, and they would fly.
And I'd never been in a unit that had airplanes before.
From that point, it got better and better and better until today.
Our airplanes will match active-duty airplanes any day of the week.
as far as quality of maintenance and flyability and the people that know how to fly them and how to fight.
In other words, from 1967 on down, you've been getting new airplanes?
No.
No.
Are you getting the airplanes that come from the active duty and they decided they get the new ones and you get their sort of hand-me-downs?
We have an Air Force base in Arizona near Phoenix called Davis-Monthan Air Force Base.
It's otherwise known as the Boneyard of the Air Force.
When the Air Force can no longer fly an airplane, they send it to the boneyard.
You use it for spare parts or for whatever.
Well, instead of sending it to Davis-Monthan, when they couldn't get another mile out of it, then they gave it to the reserves, and then we'd squeeze some more miles out of it.
That was the beginning.
That's the way the 119s worked.
When about did that start?
That's a significant change.
That happened probably in about 19...
1958, 1959, when we started getting those kinds of airplanes.
Now here, once again, I'm relying strictly on my memory.
That's fine.
Now, I could be off 10 years one way or the other.
But this is when I first had knowledge of it, to put it that way.
But then, we've always gotten our equipment from the active duty.
As they would get better equipment, we'd get their older equipment.
But the quality of the equipment we get has constantly improved
So that now, for example, in Vietnam and since then, the F-4 has been one of our primary fighter aircraft, fighter bombers, primarily a fighter.
All of our units have F-4s now.
Now, the F-105 was the plane we had prior to that, which was an excellent airplane, still an excellent airplane.
But the F-4 is coming in to take its place.
Plus, we've got a unit at Hill Air Force Base now.
getting F-16s right off the assembly line, getting ready to.
So now the reserve groups are getting brand new equipment.
It's never been flown before.
And is that since the Reagan administration?
Yes.
Is that part of the changes, do you think, of the Reagan administration?
Part of the increasing defense expenditure?
I would say that it's a result of the overall realization that we cannot afford
from a fiscal standpoint to maintain the kind of active duty air force that we need to defend the country.
But we recognize that we have to have certain squares filled in order to be able to support our various war plans.

And so if you don't have the money to support those war plans with active duty forces, then you spend the money on the reserves because you can maintain a group or a wing of reserve aircraft at a fraction of the cost that it would cost to maintain
an active duty outfit because of the fact that they work all day every day.
Sure.
Of course, your primary cost, once you get the equipment cost behind you, you've got to have the equipment, whether it's active duty or reserve.
But then once you put that to one side, then your payroll cost is your biggest single cost.
And of course, the reservist paycheck is a fraction of what an active duty paycheck would be.
But yet, he can meet the same standards, the same flying criteria, can fill the same square in a war plane that an active duty guy can fill.
So that's why the shift.
It's a matter of we can't afford the kind of active duty force we really need.
Therefore, this is the alternative we're accepting.
I think it would have come no matter who the president had been.
We got a bigger pie, but the pie is not big enough, so the reserves are getting a bigger piece of the bigger pie.
Oh, OK. OK.
So the Air Force itself has come to this realization.
Oh, yes.
Yes.
It's referred to primarily as a total force policy.
And that is a major concept.
The active duty have always, it's almost like the acceptance of minorities or women.
They've always kind of looked down their nose at reservists as being second-class citizens.
Because back in the old days, when we were called the ragtag militia,

uniforms were tattered the haircuts were bad shoes were you know well those are personal things it was all taken work real hard at improving the image of the reservist and it's paid off i think the active duty force looks at us as an equal partner in the defense establishment as opposed to a second class group of citizens and so that's why those of us in positions to to manage

other people when we find, especially at the full colonel position and above, we look at our people much more severely properly than anyone else does to make sure that when we put a guy in a full colonel's position or in a BG position that he's going to be a credit to the rest of us.
Now tell me about this total forest policy.
When did it become a volunteer?
I would say
Once again, I'm going to have to pull a figure out of the air.
Sure.
But I would say the total force policy has been established as an official policy of the Air Force, Department of the Air Force, for approximately 10 years, 8 to 10 years.
It's a relatively new concept.
All the total force policy does is to recognize the reserve forces as an integral part of the defense establishment and as an integral part
in supporting our war plans.
Always before, the war plans were supported exclusively by the active duty forces.
Now the reserves are plowed right in and cranked right in to the requirements to support war plans.
So that if we execute plan so-and-so and it calls for so many F4 units, bang, they're activated and there they go, just like an active duty outfit.
That's fantastic.
Interesting.
Yeah, it sure is interesting.
I want to talk about the change and the status of the local Air Force Reserve units.
We started this conversation a little bit ago about the history of it.
How has it changed?
And what's the chain of command?
If a young man wants to get into the Air Force Reserve here, what's the chain of command today?
And what's the status?
Actually, at the time I went to Ellington Air Force Base was when the local Air Force Reserve unit was phased out.
We have no local Air Force Reserve units here in the College Station Bryan area.
And since then, the Ellington Air Force Base unit has been transferred to Bergstrom Air Force Base at Austin, Texas.
There is no Air Force Reserve unit in Houston, the largest metropolitan area in the United States, without an Air Force Reserve unit.
Now, let me back up and say one thing that needs to be said.
When I'm talking about Air Force Reserve, well, there are two terms that let me clarify.
There's what we call Air Reserve Forces.
When you hear the term Air Reserve Forces, you're talking about Air Force Reserves and Air National Guard.
That's the Air Reserve Forces is all of the Reserve Forces.
Now, I've not talked about Guard because I know very little about the Air Force National Guard, the Air National Guard.
As you know, during peacetime, they're under the jurisdiction of the governor of the various states.
During wartime, they're nationalized, then they become a national resource.
The guard units are plowed into the warplanes just the way Air Force Reserve units are.
They do have an Air National Guard unit in Houston, but not an Air Force Reserve unit.
So if a young man wanted to get in the Air Force Reserve here, chances are his best bet would be at Austin.
Now, we...
The...
United States is divided up into what we call three numbered air forces.
They're not geographical areas.
They're divided up by weapon systems.
There's a fourth air force, which is a numbered air force commanded by a two-star reserve general located at Sacramento, California, at McClellan Air Force Base.
There's 10th Air Force, which is commanded also, all these are commanded by two-star generals.
As I mentioned, it was the highest rank that an air force reservist can hold under present law at Bergstrom Air Force Base.
And then there's 14th Air Force, which is, what is, my mind's gone blank on where the 14th Air Force is located.
Oh, we can fill it in later.
Okay, it'll come to me.
But in any event, those air forces primarily are divided up by weapons systems.
Now the 4th and the 14th on the west coast and the east coast primarily have
tactical airlift aircraft.
In other words, they have the C-130s.
Basically, the C-130 is their airplane right now for hauling things.
The 14th has things east of the Mississippi.
The 4th has things west of the Mississippi, all the units in those areas.
Whereas 10th Air Force, the headquarters at Bergstrom Air Force Base, the one I was assigned to for so many years, well, previously it was at Ellington called Central Air Force Reserve Region.
It was transferred to Bergstrom and re-designated 10th Air Force.
has all the fighters and aircraft that are primarily gained by tactical air command.
Also, we have all the aircraft that are gained by strategic air command, which includes your KC-135 tankers.
We're getting into the KC-10 tanker now at Barksdale Air Force Base.
All those assets are gained by strategic air command.
10th Air Force had responsibility for those units.
Do you have any B-1 bombers?
No, no B-1s online yet.
Do you have any B-52s?
No, not in the reserve program.
KC-135 is the tanker, which is a refueler for the B-52s.
It's the heaviest thing we've gotten into yet.
Do you think eventually you'll all get some bombers?
It's hard to say.
Strategic Air Command...
has such a quick response time in the matter of minutes that I'm not sure reservists will ever man the bombers at B-52.
That's absolutely true.
Because we have to respond in 24 hours.
SAC can't live with that kind of response.
No, absolutely.
It's 25 minutes from Moscow to .
That's right.
That's true.
But I really don't think you'll ever see any reserve bomber crews.

There was a lot of hesitancy on whether we could ever handle a reserve tanker operation, but that seemed to be working relatively well because you've got more lead time on tankers than you have on bombers and what have you.
But if someone in this area wanted to get in the reserve program, he would go to Berkshire Air Force Base.
Now, 10th Air Force is the headquarters command.
It's a giant paper mill.
It has no airplanes itself.
It manages a lot of units all over the United States that have airplanes.
One of the units, the 924th, used to be the 924th Tactical Airlift Group.
I don't know what the new designation was.
They've renumbered it since I was there.
It is located at Bergstrom Air Force Base.
So that would be the place for a young man to go.
Now, every base has what they call a reserve, an air reserve management officer, an ARMO.
Basically, he's usually a master sergeant.
our senior master sergeant, and he kind of keeps an eye on all the reserve slots on that base.
So it's a single point of contact that a young man can go say, hey, I live over at Collin Station.
I'm interested in getting a reserve program.
Is there anything here for me?
He knows where all the vacancies are, what all the skill requirements are, and he can help place individuals that have an interest in it.
I'm wondering about the relationship that you have with the Air National Guard.
Very little.
That's right.
At our level.

Now, at the air staff level, the two-star general in charge of the National Guard, General Conaway, General John Conaway, and our boss, General Sandy Gill, Air Force Reserve General, probably live together.
They're together all the time.
But below that level, we don't really have much to do with each other.
Our paths just don't cross that much.
Is there friction between the two groups?
No, not really.
Not really.

Well, I've heard that, or I have heard from some reservists, that while they are National Guard, they're just a bunch of political appointee types, and they're not really the military, and they're just good old boys.
Would you respond to them?
I will say that the National Guard has a tremendous political impact on this nation, more so than the Reserves.
primarily because of the fact that they can exert pressure through the various governors of the state.
I think it's a matter that they've just been at it longer than we have, and they've honed to perfection their abilities to muster political force when it's needed.
Obviously, the military is prohibited from participating in any political activity.
But when we're wearing our civilian clothes, like today, we're civilians, and we can call our congressman, ride the president, do whatever we want to as civilians.
And we can express an interest in things pertaining to the military, whereas an active duty guy cannot do that.
So I think the active duty force recognizes the reserve as the only shot they have at playing politics.
They don't use that in a direct way.

But through our knowing and our proximity to the military and knowing what some of our crying needs are, there's nothing that prevents us as individuals of picking up a phone and calling our congressman or when Phil Graham comes to town to see him and say, boy, we sure need some support and some aircraft spares because we're hurting bad.
Well, that brings up an interesting point, the active duty people.
perhaps using or mobilizing the reservists to put pressure on Washington.

Is there, without naming names, of course, has there been in your career any attempt for active duty officers to say, OK, you reservists, maybe at your two-week camp or something like that, OK, you reservists, go home and write your congressman about this or that?
Has there ever been any examples like that?
I've never heard of it happening.
And in fact, the active duty goes out of its way to make sure that that never happens because it's not proper.
Now, that's not to say that a lot of reservists don't do exactly the things that the active duty would like to see us do.
But it's not done at the request or at the direction of the active duty.
It's a self-initiated thing that reservists see a need because of their proximity to the situation.
and try to do something about it in their civilian capacity.
Yeah, I wouldn't think that would be.
Now, let's talk a little bit about the relationship between the Air Force Reserve in the state and the Army Reserve in the state.
Is there much of a relationship there?
No.
As long as I've been in the Reserve Program, I know absolutely nothing about the Army Reserve Program.
I know a bunch of individuals that are in the local Army Reserve.
Lynn Stewart, for example, is a good friend of mine.
Sure.
Kent Potts and Ronnie Hale and a few people like that that are close personal friends of mine.
But we've never talked about the Reserve program together other than the fact that we recognize and respect the fact that we're making a contribution in our own way.
But I've never had an interface at all with any Army Reserve outfits at all.
No Army Reservations?
no Army Reserve units than I've ever gone out with Air Force Reserve units on any type of maneuvers.
Not to my knowledge.
The only interface we've ever had is that we do furnish airlift support for some paratroop drops periodically, but we're basically flying the platform that they jump off of is what it amounts to.
But I've never been involved personally with any of that.
I know that it happens all the time, but as far as any
joint maneuvers or anything like that.
I've never been involved with it.
Let's talk a little bit about the Volunteer Army.
That must have had an impact on the reserves.
It did.
I would say that, well, once the draft was eliminated, our number of applicants dropped pretty drastically because
as we mentioned yesterday, that a number of people are inclined to prefer to serve their country in the reserve rather than to run the risk of being drafted.
Even though the risk is relatively small, the risk was there.
And some of them didn't choose to take the risk.
The minute the draft was dropped and it became all volunteer, then there was not the threat of the draft.
So therefore, they didn't need to seek an alternative.
So it had a definite impact on our recruiting.
I would say that the impact was relatively short lived.

I sense, and I think I've talked to a number of other people that sense, that there's a kind of a rebirth of nationalism in this country, that there seems to be almost a wave of patriotism sweeping the country that's been absent for a long time.
I think it's kind of a digging out the quagmire of Vietnam.

At the time, the Vietnamese situation was going and up to and immediately after the cessation of hostilities, I would say that the military was at an all-time low in this country in the eyes of the citizen on the street.
It was almost an insult to be in a uniform.
I've been in airports and in public places in my uniform where people would
people would drive by in the car and yell obscenities to you.
No kidding.
Instead of being- Was that at the end of the war?
Early 70s?
Yeah, in that time period.
As a result, we're encouraged never to wear a uniform, especially a general officer never wears a uniform when he's going public transportation or what have you.
No kidding.
We always go in civilian clothes because, first of all- That's a response?
That's a response of the post-Vietnam era?
That-
plus the increasing instance of terrorism.
Now, not so much in this country, but overseas.
You've made the General Dozier instance and things of that type.
They don't like you to play up the fact that you're a general officer.
In fact, I've worn this pin ever since my little tie pin with my star ever since I was promoted.
Most of the general officers have a bumper sticker on the car with the number of stars that you're entitled to.
First of all, because they give you preferred parking places at certain places, like from the officer's club, you know, you've got a reserved general officer, little bennies that go with it.
But they're even talking now about eliminating those because they don't want you to be known as a general officer because of the potential for terrorist kidnapping or what have you.
What does that do to morale?
Well, you know, it's kind of...
I mean, you've worked this long, and now you can't even wear your uniform.
That really hasn't come into being yet.
There's just some talk about it.
I do know that they've issued bumper stickers now with the capital letter G on it instead of the star.
Of course, it doesn't take very many brains to figure out what the G stands for.
But it's not critical in this country, but in an overseas assignment,
you have to assume that someone's trying to kill you or kidnap you all the time if you're a general officer.
And it's not a bad assumption because it's true in a lot of places.
Yeah.
But here, when you're on public transportation, here, do you wear your uniform when you don't?
No.
And that's Air Force directive?
Well, it's Air Force policy.
I don't think there's anything in writing.
It's just that when we have meetings, and we have meetings twice a year of all Air Force Reserve general officers,
And they're mirrors almost of some of the active duty general officer meetings that they have.
We're told that it's Air Force policy that you not travel in your military uniform on public conveyance.
And when you travel in military aircraft, of course, then you have to have on uniform.
But if you're riding public transportation, airplanes, trains, buses, you never travel in uniform.
They even discourage full colonels from doing it.
But general officers, you just don't do it.
And it's because of the fact that you're going to get heckled by certain elements, not so much now as immediately right after the Vietnamese.
But you know, it's almost unbelievable that someone in the uniform of their country, trying to serve their country, would be heckled for having that uniform on.
I know.
But it happens.
I know.
It's incredible, just a little aside here.
But as I mentioned, that's when we hit rock bottom.
And I think it's continued to improve since then.
And I think that this country is on the verge of giving a lot of respect and having a lot of patriotic fervor that we've not had for years.
I think that Reagan has really got his hands full on what he's going to do in Central and South America.

I think that without any question in my mind, the threat in Central and South America is at least as substantial as Nazi Germany's threat during the Second World War and maybe worse because of its proximity to our country.
To me, that threat far overshadows anything that Korea or Vietnam could have ever done to us.
To me, this is the single most
serious threat to our survival as a country that I can imagine.
And yet we've got people in Congress right now that are saying, let those people work out their own problems.
And it just doesn't work that way.
Well, let's talk a little bit more about the draft and the volunteer army.
And you have to forgive me for chasing these rabbits when they come.
Oh, that's fine.
I want your ideas and your opinions.
I want your ideas on the draft.
Do you think that we should reinstate the draft?
Without any question, I'd do it before noon today if I had the authority.
I see no reason why a certain segment of our society should defend this country and another segment, because of their affluence, never have to do it.
I think that people from all walks of life should serve this country equally, either voluntarily or if they have to be made to do it, then let's make them do it.
But we all know that the people in the lower economic stratus make up the bulk of the military.
By the same token, you don't have that vast cross-section and the thinking and the expertise of a good cross-section of the country that we had during the draft.
You've got a distorted view of what the world's all about because you're drawing from only one segment of the society.
And I'm speaking primarily of the enlisted corps now.
The officer corps, I think, you've got a pretty good cross section.
The officer corps is pretty well educated, more so than the regular society, because you've got to have a college degree.
And I would say that with rare exceptions, you'll never see anybody reach the rank of full colonel or above without a master's degree.
For general officers, it's becoming more common that you have a PhD to become a general officer.
And I don't have one, but I think in the future,
That's almost going to be part of one of the squares to fill.
But I don't think you'll ever see a full colonel, very many full colonels in the future without a master's degree.
To me, this relates fairly well with what happens in the civilian segment of our society, not so in the enlisted grades.
So back to your original question, I can't tell you how strongly I feel that we should reinstate the draft, even in peacetime.
Now, it sounds to me that you see the draft more as
Oh, something to increase the amount of citizenship.
Absolutely.
I think it's a civic responsibility to defend this country.
And you also see it in class, as far as class terms.
That is, the middle and the upper middle class.
And upper class is a college, a suburban class.
They don't have to serve, but others do.
And you think that's unfair.
I think it's unfair in that, first of all, I think every citizen has an obligation to do their share.
But second of all, I think once people get into the military, that they themselves get something from it.
I think those people are being deprived of the privilege of serving their country.
And so I know a lot of people that say, boy, I would have never volunteered for that, but I'm sure glad I had the experience.
And so you put someone in the position where they have to perform, and then later on, they're proud they had the experience.
And they would not have done it had they not been made to do it.
But I think that there's just no question whatsoever in my mind of, first of all, us having a better military if we did it that way.
Because even if a guy doesn't want to do something, if he's placed in a position, most people can do the best they can with what they've got.
And so I think that not only would we have a better military,
But I think you'd have more patriotism in this country because more people would be touched with it in a direct basis.
Wealthy families may go for generations without ever having a member of their family ever serve a day in the military.
That's criminal.
What a privilege that they've missed.
What about women?
Do you think women in America should also serve in the military?
In today's environment, I do.
I think they should be drafted right along with men.
And here, once again, you've got the question of who you draft.
But we've always had that question, and it worked relatively well.
You register everyone.
And the lottery wasn't a bad way to do it.
At least you get a good cross section.
I feel that whether anybody wants to admit it or not, there are differences between men and women.
I think in combat situations where you
are living off the land without any latrine facilities or anything like that, it would be a mistake to put women into a combat situation.
But there are lots of ways they can serve without being in the trenches on the front lines.

In other words, do you agree with old Harry Truman's idea of the universal military training, that everyone, when they turn a certain age, 18 or 19, should have a year or two of some sort of service to the country?
Or do you think that's too broad and too expensive?
I would like to see it, but I think from a practical standpoint that that would be too expensive.

I feel that everyone should register, that there possibly should be a certain amount of indoctrination required in conjunction with that registration, maybe a half a day of some very basics about what our country is all about.
And then if they're fortunate enough or unfortunate enough, depending on how they view it, to be selected for the draft, then I think that should be done.
so that you've got a good cross-section of this country defending the country.
And not only that individual, but also the impact that individual has on his immediate family and his neighbors and friends and what have you.
There are parts of Houston that you could go into and probably go for 40 houses, and they don't have anybody in the military and never have had anybody in the military since the draft.
It's not right.
So...
You probably didn't want to know that.
I want all that.
As a matter of fact, I have very similar feelings.
Being a veteran, I have very similar feelings on that.
And I want to know this.
There's another thing that I'd like to know.
Sometimes, especially during the Vietnamese War, a lot of journalists said that there was such a thing as a military mentality.
That was usually the term they used, that there was a way that the military thinks about it.
Well, you're both in an institution and you're in another institution, the military, and I was wondering what you thought.
Is there such a thing as a military mentality, and if so, what is it?

I would think that if there is such a thing, that it would be a normal outgrowth of having been in a profession for a number of years in which you tend to accept the policies that are established by the military establishment as your own policies.
I don't mean that people follow the party line right down to the nth degree, but chances are,
Just like here, if Dr. Vannevar wants to do something, I don't have any strong objections not to do it, well then I adopt that as my policy because I'm supporting Dr. Vannevar and his ideas.
The same thing is true in the military.
I would say that you wouldn't find any difference in the military
way of responding to suggestions and policies adopted by their superiors than you would find in the civilian sector.
OK. And I wanted to ask you another question on that, as far as advancement.
You've advanced substantially in both the military and in university.
And before that, you were for Sears and Roebuck.
Now I'm wondering, and for a while you even had your own company.
I'm wondering if it's the same type
characteristics that make someone a success in the military as in private or in public institutions?
Absolutely.
I don't think there's any difference.
I think it's a situation of learning a skill, filling the squares, doing the job.
But to me, I think that success in private business, success within a corporate structure, or success in the military, assuming that you're doing the technical side of your job,
is primarily a matter of attitude and personality, human relations.
Those things are 80% of it.
Only 20% of it is skill and knowledge, in my opinion.
And that's true in the military or wherever you go.
When you think back on your career, which of course isn't completed yet, but when you think back on it, do you see yourself now as ambitious?
That's a hard one.
Sure is.

I don't see myself as ambitious for ambition's sake to attain a certain, in other words, I've never had the ambition to be a two-star general for the sake of just saying, look at me, I'm a two-star general.
I'm ambitious from the point that I like responsibility.
I like accomplishing work.
I like delegating and working through people.
And I'd be less than honest if I didn't say that I like a certain amount of authority to be able to direct things and make things happen that I think should happen.
But as a result of doing these things, if promotions and recognition come as a result, then that's great.
But that's not the primary goal.
The goal is to do something, hopefully that would be a benefit to whatever organization I'm talking about,
whether it be the military, whether it be Texas A&M, whether it be my church, whether it be my family.
Do the best you can with the jobs at hand, and then if recognition and promotions come, well and good.

Well, did you leave on the way up the ladder then to success, did you leave that advancement to fate or luck, or do you think that that advancement was because you accomplished those individual tasks?
I think
I think the accomplishment of individual tasks was only part of it.

I think the secret to my advancement and the secret to almost anyone's advancement has a whole lot to do with proximity to power sources, knowing people that are in a position to promote you, knowing people that are in a position to recommend you for certain jobs, doing a job
that they become aware of, whether it's from their own initiative or whether you make sure that they are aware of what you're doing.
I have no big hang up with blowing your own horn, as long as it's done for the proper motives and as long as it's honest and true.
As long as you're not inflating yourself.
That's right.
That's right.
Of course, we're on another thin sheet of ice here.
That's true.
On what is the question between realistically saying, here's what I have achieved, and then inflating what you've done and boasting.
That's right.
It's a matter of personal integrity as to whether you do that or not.
Chances are you could.
But almost always, when you inflate something, it's going to catch up with you.
And our superiors should see it.
That's true.
But I would think that not being afraid to speak up, to introduce yourself six, eight, 10 times if necessary, until somebody learns your name.
I got real tickled at the last board meeting.
I was to give a report to the board on the parking conditions over and around the vet college.
And I've only been a vice president since last October, so I don't know all the board.
Well, I know all the board members, but they all don't know me.
So I've had a great deal of difficulty in the few times that they are on campus for them to learn my name.
And most of them know my face and know that I'm connected with the physical plant in some way or the police, but they don't know my name.
So finally, I'd introduce myself to Mr. Joe Richardson, who's the chairman of our building committee a number of times, and just a super guy.
And so it came to my part on the program.
He says, OK.
He says, I've asked Dr. Vandiver to put together a report on parking conditions and a petition that some of the vet students had put together for us.
And he says, and he's asked Chuck to give the report.
And I thought, thank goodness.
Boy, he finally learned my name.
He says, and now to give the report is Chuck McCandless.
So I thought, well, I'm halfway home.
So Dr. Vandiver corrected him.
And then he later on told me he's sure sorry that he tried to remember my name as Cargill.
But anyway.
There's all the board members sitting around, so I'll probably be Chuck McCandless to them for the rest of their life because, of course, Chuck has appeared before the board a number of times.
But name recognition is so important.
Letting people know that you want to do what you can to help them with their programs.
If you can help enough other people get what they want, then you'll get what you want.
It's a service-oriented type philosophy, but you've also got to be a little bit pushy in letting people know that,
Hey, if there's something else I can do to help you with that, let me know.
Be willing to accept the responsibility and help the guy with his problems, and he'll love you for it.
And he'll promote you for it.
And it's something that you're accomplishing your objectives to, and that's to be of more service to whatever organization it may be.
I want to talk about that and accomplishments.

When you look back on your career in the military, and of course this is a question that's premature because you might be at the point of your career where you're going to have the most impact on the Air Force.
But when you look back at your career, what do you see as accomplishments in the reserves?
And I also want you to think, was there anything that you thought were shortcomings?

I would think that probably the period of time, not a specific instance, but a period of time in which a number of things happened that I point to with pride more than just about any other, was the time that I served as a full colonel at 10th Air Force Headquarters as Director of Logistics Plan for the 10th Air Force.
During that period of time, we performed what we call staff assistance visits to our units, which were all over the United States.
We had put together a team from the headquarters.
And as a full colonel, I was frequently the team chief, which is another way of saying the highest-ranking guy in charge of the team.
Anywhere from 20 to 40 people would come on an airplane, and we'd go visit our units.
They called them inspections, and that's really what they were.
But we didn't like the word inspection.
We called them staff assistance visits.
And they say the two biggest lies ever told in the Air Force is when the team gets off, the team chief said, we're here to help you, and the guy that you're visiting said, we're glad to see you.
And those are the two biggest lies I've ever told.
But anyway.
But during that period of time, when I was team chief, visiting these units all over the United States, I consider that to be my most productive time as far as making a contribution.
Because, of course, those of us that were specialists in certain areas could go in and look at their records, look at their programs, look at their in-commission rates and so forth.
check some of their supplies to see how long it's been since certain wear date items like rubber can't stay in a kit too long because it gets hard and you've got to replace it.
And those kinds of things, I feel we've really made a contribution toward the readiness of the reserve program.
But I look at that as my most productive time as far as making a contribution.
When you become a general officer, you've got to define the word general.
It means a general officer as opposed to a specialist officer.
Up to that point, you're a specialist in some field.
You become a general officer.
You could be in personnel.
You could be in supply.
You could be anywhere.
Because supposedly, you have a broad enough concept of the entire picture, the big picture, that you could fit in anywhere.
And the active Air Force uses its people that way, too.
My boss right now at Tinker Air Force Base was at SAC headquarters.
Never has spent one day in supply, but yet he's a commander of one of the largest supply and maintenance operations in the entire world.
